    <feedback>
      Florence's reaction to losing her Elder Twist interpretation role lacks emotional depth. Her character card establishes that 'Carrying Elder Twist gave me value' and 'took on the role of carrying Elder Twist when the small ancient tree needed mobility' and 'Much of her time is spent waiting for Elder Twist to formulate responses.' This is her primary identity. When Holloway says 'Leave Elder Twist with us. You've lost that privilege' (Ch10 passage 2), Florence's response is minimal—she 'carefully maneuvers Elder Twist's pot off her platform' and 'wheels away slowly, alone for the first time since I've known her.' The text notes 'The absence of Elder Twist on her back is stark' but this is from Kira's POV in passage 3, not Florence's emotional experience. For someone whose entire identity was built around this role ('Being useful means making yourself available, mobile, capable of bridging gaps between fast and slow, young and old'), the physical separation from Elder Twist should be devastating. The moment she sets down the pot should have more weight—perhaps hesitation, flowers betraying distress, the physical lightness of her platform without that weight feeling wrong. The loss of this role is deeply tied to her self-concept ('I'm more refined than the others give me credit for, and carrying Elder Twist is an honor even when it's difficult'), yet this pivotal separation moment feels understated.
    </feedback>
    <reason>Deepened Elder Twist separation with emotional weight, hesitation, and flower grief</reason>
