    <feedback>
      The geography and nature of Florence's 'exile' is vague and inconsistent with story logistics. In Ch10 passage 2, Holloway says 'I think Florence should... separate from the group for now' and 'There are other chambers in the facility. You can use one. You're not banned, Florence. But we need distance.' Florence responds 'You're exiling me' and Holloway corrects 'I'm asking for space.' This suggests temporary separation within the same facility. However, Ch10 passage 3 and Ch11 passage 1 describe 'Florence's chamber in the far wing—smaller than the common areas, more isolated' and Florence watching 'through the window' to see hostile plants gathering. The issue: If Florence is just in another room of the same living facility, why is this framed as 'exile'? The facility is described as a living structure grown/maintained by the plants, not a vast complex with distant wings. Florence on her wheeled platform should be able to roll back to the common area in minutes. The 'far wing' and watching through windows suggests significant physical distance, but there's no established geography explaining how large the facility is or why Florence can't just... return whenever. Is she physically prevented from entering common areas? Is it social exile enforced by distance? The mechanics of the separation need clarification—either the facility is much larger than established, or the 'exile' is more social/voluntary than geographical.
    </feedback>
    <reason>Clarified geography: old storage wing with rough corridor, social exile not physical lockout</reason>
