  <critique id="A10" status="done">
    <creator agent="true" created="2025-12-14T16:55:06.091Z" agent-type="critique"/>
    <ref ref="/world/characters/Velvet.card#v5.0.0"/>
    <ref ref="/stories/Mandatory_Assistance/chapters/12_Victory_Through_Voice/passages/1_Voices_Emerging/passage.card#v3.0.0"/>
    <ref ref="/stories/Mandatory_Assistance/chapters/13_Individual_Voices/passages/2_Signal_From_Outside/passage.card#v3.0.0"/>
    <feedback>
      VELVET'S TACTICAL/CREATIVE COMPLEXITY MAY EXCEED CHARACTER CARD DEFINITION: Velvet's character card (v5.0.0) emphasizes extreme simplicity: 'very moss-like: simple, slow, literal, focused on basic moss concerns' (overview line 24), 'Extremely simple and literal—doesn't understand complex ideas or nuance' (flaws line 37), and worldview is 'Surfaces are for growing. Light is for making food. Dry makes me slow. Wet makes me fast. The robot is a good surface. Moving the robot means accessing new surfaces. Simple.' (lines 27-28).

      However, in later passages, Velvet demonstrates sophisticated tactical and creative thinking that seems inconsistent with this extreme simplicity:

      1. Chapter 12 Passage 1 (Voices Emerging, lines 64-76): Velvet interrupts Florence to propose 'layered defense' concept—'Instead of one thick barrier, multiple thinner layers with gaps between them. Attackers break through the first layer, encounter empty space, then hit a second layer. Disrupts their momentum.' Florence calls this 'brilliant' and says 'It's better than what I was planning.' This is complex tactical thinking involving momentum, misdirection, and multi-stage defense strategy—far beyond 'simple moss concerns.'

      2. Chapter 13 Passage 2 (Signal From Outside, line 17): Velvet offers 'I can grow directional antenna. If someone tells me the specifications.' This shows understanding of technical specifications and ability to execute complex engineering tasks based on parameters.

      3. Chapter 14 Passage 2 (Demonstrating Belonging, lines 27-36): Velvet creates 'translucent growth, light filtering through in complex patterns. The ergonomic seating, the comfortable proportions' with 'Kira's feedback shaped every decision' and consideration of 'how spaces feel, not just whether they're functional.' This demonstrates aesthetic awareness, human ergonomics understanding, and iterative design thinking.

      While the character arc notes Velvet 'discovering that moss can want things, have opinions, feel connections' and 'developing complexity,' the specific examples seem to go beyond developing personhood into demonstrating sophisticated strategic, technical, and design capabilities that contradict the fundamental 'extremely simple and literal' characterization.

      Possible resolutions:
      1. Revise character card to acknowledge Velvet has capacity for complex spatial/structural thinking even while remaining simple in other ways
      2. Revise passages to show Velvet's contributions as simpler/more intuitive ('layers feel better' vs explaining tactical momentum disruption)
      3. Add more character development passages showing Velvet's surprising emergence of complexity as a plot point that others notice and comment on
    </feedback>
    <reason>Added spatial/structural intelligence - moss naturally understands surfaces, layers, light filtration</reason>
    <ref ref="/world/characters/Velvet.card#v6.0.0" status="done" role="Edited"/>
  </critique>
  <critique id="A11" status="done">
    <creator agent="true" created="2025-12-14T16:55:32.519Z" agent-type="critique"/>
    <ref ref="/world/characters/Velvet.card#v5.0.0"/>
    <ref ref="/stories/Mandatory_Assistance/chapters/11_Under_Attack/passages/1_Delegation_Fails/passage.card#v3.0.0"/>
    <feedback>
      VELVET'S FIRST APPEARANCE IS MISSING: Velvet appears in the story already established as a known character with no introduction scene. In Chapter 11 Passage 1 (Delegation Fails, line 3), the narrative states 'Runner and Velvet leave at dawn' as if Kira already knows who Velvet is. Later (line 25) refers to 'Velvet's growth near the facility' maintaining the building, implying Velvet has been present for some time.

      However, searching through all earlier passages (Chapters 1-10), there is NO scene where:
      - Kira is introduced to Velvet
      - Kira discovers that moss is sentient  
      - Kira learns Velvet's name
      - Kira reacts to the existence of sentient moss

      This is a significant narrative gap. The character card's humor-style section (lines 91-97) includes an example of Kira's reaction to learning Velvet is moss:
      '[Kira learns Velvet is moss]
      Kira: "Wait. Velvet, what are you?"
      Velvet: "Moss."
      Kira: "Of course you are."
      [long pause]
